Anyone who smokes has a higher risk of losing teeth.
Smoking damages not only the lungs, but also the teeth - this is suggested by a long-term Potsdam study.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk drops quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is the result of a long-term study by an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at risk of losing their teeth prematurely, 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth failure are caries and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
Smoking is a risk factor for this periodontitis, the authors emphasize.
The link between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gingivitis in smokers.
It is unclear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
However, people who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it may take more than ten years for the risk to drop back to the level of non-smokers, first author Thomas Dietrich of the English University of Birmingham explained.
One must convince people to become non-smokers, said Heiner Boeing, director of the DIfE: “Smoking shortens the lifetime.”
Not to smoke is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health up to old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 years are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE said.
Previous research had already suggested that smoking increases the risk of early tooth failure.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
