EU Commission proposes new court in dispute over TTIP
To alleviate the dispute over the planned transatlantic free trade agreement TTIP, the EU Commission has proposed a major reform of the current arbitration system.
The controversial private arbitration bodies for disputes between corporations and states should therefore be replaced by a more transparent system, which in its functioning corresponds to significantly more traditional courts.
"We want to set up a system that citizens trust," said Commissioner Cecilia Malmström.
Sweden intends to include the proposal as a European negotiating position in the free trade talks with the US.
The German government announced support.
TTIP is the world’s largest free trade zone with 800 million people.
The plans to reform the current arbitration procedures specifically require the EU states and the US to jointly select independent judges for a new investment court.
They are supposed to come to equal parts from the EU, the US and third countries.
For the first time, a second instance is also envisaged.
It would allow you to object to judgments.
So far, the parties to the proceedings have agreed on arbitrators among themselves, and there has been no possibility of appeal against their judgments.
In the discussion over the past few months, it became clear that citizens did not trust the old ISDS system in terms of fairness and justice, Malmström commented.
In the long term, she intends to work towards an International Investment Court.
There, for example, disputes between Chinese companies and EU countries could be resolved.
The investor-state arbitration (ISDS) is one of the main reasons for the great opposition in Europe to TTIP.
Traditional arbitration courts are criticised by opponents as a kind of parallel justice whereby companies can claim damages at the expense of taxpayers, defy national laws or enforce lower consumer and environmental standards.
In initial statements, anti-TTIP organizations such as Campact described the EU Commission’s proposals as insufficient.
In particular, it was criticised that they should not apply to the already negotiated free trade agreement with Canada (CETA).
German Economic Secretary Matthias Machnig (SPD), on the other hand, described the plans as great progress.
The Commission takes into account key points that Federal Minister for Economic Affairs Sigmar Gabriel worked out with other EU Trade Ministers in the spring.
The old system of private arbitration is off the table.
The French government also welcomed Malmström’s plans.
The European business association BusinessEurope warned against limiting the possibilities of lawsuits for the economy due to too many new rules.
Small and medium-sized enterprises in particular could be disadvantaged, it said.
When the talks on the TTIP (Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership) could be concluded remained unclear on Wednesday.
Negotiations have been ongoing since mid-2013.
The issue of investor protection has not yet been discussed with the United States.
Initially, a framework for the agreement should already be in place by the end of this year.
This date is deemed no longer valid.
