Jeremy Corbyn's Debut at Prime Minister's Question Time
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn’s debut at the Prime Minister’s Question Time is eagerly awaited
The new Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut at the Prime Minister's Question Time and deal with David Cameron for the first time.
Mr. Corbyn will rise to ask the first of his six predetermined questions shortly after noon, with his performance likely being closely reviewed by the media and the Labour MPs.
He called for "less theater and more facts" at this weekly event.
He also said he could skip a few sessions to leave them to colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary scrutiny for Mr Corbyn’s leadership, as it comes after his appointment as a member of the shadow cabinet and after his speech at the TUC annual meeting on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour chairman’s decision to remain silent on Tuesday during the singing of the national anthem at a commemoration of the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has provoked criticism from a number of Tory MPs and is the focus of several cover stories in the newspapers.
Mr. Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has drawn attention
A spokesman for Corbyn said he had "confessed in respectful silence" and acknowledged "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the air battle for England."
But a member of Mr Corbyn’s shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told the BBC Two Newsnight program that he had advised the Labour chairman to sing the national anthem, “independent” of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Almost a dozen shadow ministers have refused to serve on Mr Corbyn’s top team, citing differences in business, defense and foreign policy, while less than a sixth of the Parliamentary Party originally supported him as its leader.
BBC Political Correspondent Robin Brant says that political differences are also “stacking up” within Labour, following Mr Corbyn’s statements on the position on the European Union and the limitation of profits.
Mr Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labour was making changes to remove the whole idea of a limitation overall.
Hours later, Mr. Smith, the shadow labor and retirement minister, said the party was "very clear" that it was only against government plans to lower the limit from <0xC2><0xA3>26,000 to <0xC2><0xA3>23,000.
Mr. Corbyn will be the fifth Labour president to face David Cameron, since he is Tory chief, across the dispatch box in parliament in the last decade.
The Labour chairman, who promised a different policy approach, says he has "crowd-sourced" ideas for questions to Mr Cameron and has been given more than 30,000 suggestions.
The Islington North MP has said that the prime minister’s question hour is too confrontational, and that he is refraining from both “beating skill” and struggling with backlash, and has instead set out to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality, and the challenges facing young people.
Mr. Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the shadow economic minister, will represent him if he does not attend—for example, if Mr. Cameron is traveling abroad.
He also raised the idea that other colleagues occasionally take the floor, and that he addressed John Bercow, the Speaker of the House of Commons, to discuss the issue.
When he became a leader in 2005, Mr Cameron said he wanted to move away from politics in the style of a "Kasperle Theatre", which is often linked to the Prime Minister's Question Time, but a few years later he admitted that he had failed.
Since it was first broadcast on television in 1990, the Question Time with the Prime Minister was considered the most important barometer of a leader's judgment and his leadership in the House of Commons and his position among his parliamentary colleagues, although critics have argued that it has become a caricature and needs far-reaching reforms.
