Metcash launches groundworthiness campaign to combat Aldi invasion
Metcash tries to protect the IGA branches from an Aldi march in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a groundworthiness campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia at the beginning of next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as through events such as Adelaide Show.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands like Dunsborough ice cream maker Simmo distributing samples in IGA stores and store owners selling discounted South Australian Football League tickets to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, as the food, alcohol and equipment wholesaler conducts its annual investor strategy day.
There’s a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia make up nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the Eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the Eastern states.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snatch away around five percent of the food market in these two states and will take away sales from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and grocery store and in the volumes on Metcash’s high fixed cost base could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr. Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash’s food and grocery sales to fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017, and 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a Melbourne business dinner that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash refused to publicly respond to Mr Douglass’ comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash’s food and food trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reduction while simultaneously pressuring revenue and margins.
However, the wholesaler is resisting and investing more than $150 million to align retail prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week, improving IGA retailers in improving their stores by faster growing fresh foods and delivering a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash’s CEO, Ian Morrice, says price adjustments and store renovation programs will increase in momentum and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is supported by President of the Australian Tennis Federation Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damages" in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to the president of the Australian Tennis Federation Steve Healy, deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behavior.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, often referred to as "Special Ks", was spotlighted by Kyrgios' infamous encounter with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison exclaiming, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a spasm thwarted a potential U.S. Open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against the United Kingdom.
"One thing I'm pretty jealous about is the fact that, in my opinion, Thanasi was pulled a little into the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a club when he lost in the US Open because of a spasm, but he's not the first player to break a club out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he’s behaved extremely well in the U.S. Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he was treated a little too harshly.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the locker room, he trains hard, he is in good shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I believe he deserves to be judged according to his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to take Kyrgios into account in the important preliminary decision that starts on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the man from Canberra to return to the team as a long-term solid component."
"First, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I think Nick has made the ascent very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time out of the limelight I can think of it is best for him, and in the limelight I can think of it is best for him.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes the border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared the state of emergency and closed off the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man’s-land and Serbian officials reacted with indignation.
The people who had fled violence stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants shouted "Open the border!" and shouted insults against the Hungarian emergency police.
Some refused food and water in protest.
Serbia’s foreign minister said it was “unacceptable” for migrants to be sent back from Hungary as more and more migrants arrive from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
Talks with Brussels and other countries must take place in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came one day after the 28-nation bloc was unable to agree on a common immigration policy at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
However, the ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in overrun Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU states would take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special European Union summit on Tuesday to discuss the immigration crisis of the continent.
Hungary, however, did not place its hopes on a swift action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency declared on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and accelerate asylum procedures.
Meanwhile, Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it finished a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D’Agata reported that even prison inmates were used in the race to build the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck and a point of entry into the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most incoming economic refugees are in search of a better life, not war refugees who are entitled to protection – a view that is strongly opposed to other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime. These laws also set higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by the mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament still has to approve the military deployment expected for next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Orban National Security Advisor Gyorgy Bakondi said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train wagon with barbed wire to close the borders arrived.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process the data of people and pressed a crowd to push into it.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands stayed outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main motorway link from Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
2016 election: Hillary Clinton’s lead over Bernie Sanders halved in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the democratic race for the nomination at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders gains ground against her.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primary elections (58 percent before), while Sanders ranks second, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether to run for the presidency, has received support from 15 percent of the primary voters.
More than five months before the start of the primary elections, most Democratic voters say it is too early to say that their opinion is clear on which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their elections than the other candidates.
Since the CBS News survey, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some profits.
Clinton holds a great lead among women and moderates, but these lead have diminished.
Their support with the men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind here.
Clinton’s advantage over democratic voters under the age of 50 has vanished, and she and Sanders are now on par.
However, Clinton still has a big advantage over older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a two-digit lead with the Liberals, but Sanders now has a 5-point lead with this group.
About half of the Democratic primary voters across the country say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would support her only because she is the candidate.
6% would not support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are especially enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed among those who currently do not support Clinton – only about a quarter would enthusiastically support her.
While 48 percent of primary voters say they support Clinton with enthusiasm, fewer Republican voters say so about their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it’s time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she’s the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton’s supporters also mention their connection with Bill Clinton (9 percent).
Consent to deal with the problems and eligibility are also quoted.
As the vice president throws a potential for the presidency into the balance, 57 percent of primary voters want to see him in the race – though a third believe he shouldn’t.
When Democratic primary voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
More than half of Clinton’s supporters say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton’s lead over Sanders will increase from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chance of winning the election; however, that number has dropped by 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second in this measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the “most selectable” has risen.
Nevertheless, when it comes to the question of what is more important in a candidate, Democratic voters call questions about eligibility.
Similar to last month, not a single Democratic candidate or potential candidate for these primary voters stands out as unacceptable.
The Democratic candidates or potential candidates produce good results on some important characteristics among voters of their party’s primary elections.
Majorities consider Clinton, Sanders, and Biden to be honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership skills.
Biden scores best in honesty among the three candidates, while Clinton’s strength is the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters do not believe that Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say so about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent do not have an opinion about him.
Democratic primary voters generally also see Clinton, Sanders and Biden as ideologically consistent with their views.
With all these measurements, about a quarter of Democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions continue to be asked about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and server during her tenure as Secretary of State, most Democratic primary voters are satisfied with her explanation of the matter, saying it hasn’t influenced their opinions overall.
But it’s a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no effect on their general opinions about Clinton, though 36 percent said their opinion about her had worsened.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views on Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party voters, this remains a problem for her among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see her as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month and 15 points less since May.
62 percent of voters do not consider her to be an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters across the country also see Trump as not honest and untrustworthy.
However, Clinton and Trump get good grades in leadership.
Of the six tested candidates, Biden, Carson, and Bush cut best in honesty.
A majority view Sanders more than honestly, but as with Carson, many do not have an opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primary elections is 6 percentage points.
