Five Brotherhood members charged with the death of Baruch College newcomer
Almost two years after a student died during a harassment ritual of a student connection in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of New York’s Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun “Michael” Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013, delaying his transportation to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he was loaded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand with blindfolded eyes, and repeatedly attacked while trying to walk across a frozen field to a target.
Mr. Deng finally complained of a headache, then fell unconscious.
The members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng fainted and reportedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng’s clothes, google his symptoms, and contact Andy Meng, the national president of the Brotherhood, to seek advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide utensils and basically put the welfare of the Brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," said police chief Wagner.
He could not be resurrected, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
According to an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly injured with blunt force to the head, torso and thighs.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the harassment of the Brotherhood, and at least one student dies every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A County Grand Jury of Monroe recommended a charge for third-degree murder for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also being charged with harassment and forming a criminal association.
"Not only do we want to blame the people involved, but if there is an organization that has sanctioned this - officially or unofficially - we will also hold them accountable," Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
The Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its affiliation to the local group.
This will happen if the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the boom will stagger, bond yields will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will take and how long it will last.
In particular, the history offers little guidance for the economy on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first interest rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. Central Bank have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when it starts to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that all the excitement may have been exaggerated due to an interest rate hike.
“The Fed’s first increase since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of “cheap money,” said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal levels, but still at too low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here is a historical trend-based look at how some areas of the economy might react:
As the market has seen last month, anticipating interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase occurs, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for asset earnings to be strangled 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may reflect the delay in monetary policy,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has mostly been on the uptrend over the past 35 years – about 14 percent – heading for interest rate hikes, fairly flat in the 250 days following (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the past six cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategy officer at Nuronve Management.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the stocks tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the return begins to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often promote them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely noteworthy here that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point at a Fed interest rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes in such a fragile economic setting could be risky and raise the question “if it’s different this time,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been preparing for a Fed interest rate hike throughout the year, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only gives a 25 percent probability.
"In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to the present day took place in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP and very quickly overshadowed pre-recession highs after the start of the recovery," the report said.
In contrast, this is clearly a slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
The fixed income was also volatile, as the market anticipates an interest rate hike, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic course.
In the case of bonds, returns seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/lower occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields are falling immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will bring yields between longer and shorter bonds closer together and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we’re still cautious about expecting higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones says markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some indications that the market has adapted to the outlook for tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have expanded and volatility has risen – all characteristics of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
By and large, companies operating the bulk of their business in the US will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational corporations with high debt will be worse off, as a rising dollar will make their products more expensive in the global market, as well as financing their debt.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Companies with a strong balance sheet have surpassed companies with a weak balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits from higher returns, even if experts disagree on how fast this will take place.
