At their most anticipated meeting in the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table to decide if it’s time to raise the policy rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening above them at one end of the decorated, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the economic interests of the nation above all other things.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices here stable.
But since the Great Recession, the Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X-Factor in a decision too narrow to predict. It will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to start being weaned from the unprecedented incentive of the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows it’s growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could make the already cautious Fed representatives anxious to amplify this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds — even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing they are watching," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economics officer at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to keep waiting," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself uncertaints the financial market.
About half of the economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg have predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a fall in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped by 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that the Fed’s policies will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise the rates at this point," he said.
If she does, “she would have to go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would eliminate the uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen had said in spring and early summer that she expects an increase in the rate this year despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, the improvement in the labour market this year was solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed sees as full employment.
Salary increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was constantly below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of the tightening of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world shrank at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May, when investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would thwart global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the May high.
For the Fed representatives, market turbulence affects the complex calculation of when to increase interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news of the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would have pulled the reins in this session,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former US Federal Reserve employee.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main concerns, so it should not be technically included in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere indication by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “tighten” its monetary expansion sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that "the Fed has a history of overreaction to financial market movements that seem to be unrelated to economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, who advocates an interest rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its policy rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions “despite limited noticeable impact on U.S. growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market collapse, said Adam S. Posen, former member of the Bank of England Interest Rate Setting Committee.
The recent turbulences are not coming close to this level, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into a situation where she’s afraid of an interest rate hike because markets are getting upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should be ahead of time.
