Four-fold increase in children taking hand sanitizers in the last 4 years
Poison control centers in the U.S. report an almost 400 percent increase in the number of children under the age of twelve who take heavily alcoholic hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of hand disinfectant intake among children under the age of 12 reported by poison control centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are getting these products more and more frequently, and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up going to the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children deliberately drink disinfectants while some do it to impress their friends or because of a test of courage on social media.
Videos on YouTube show how teens drink disinfectants just for a cheap experience.
Teenagers have allegedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted by attractive scents of disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for it,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand disinfectants) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scent that are very appealing to children.
Hand disinfectants contain between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in toddlers, a few splashes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol," Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison emergency call center at the University of Kansas hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansa City.
So, you wouldn’t leave a sip of whiskey around, but people leave these hand disinfectants within reach of children, and if children get it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four splashes of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice the threshold legally considered drunk in an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside of Atlanta.
Nhaijah laughed at her words and was unable to walk when she arrived in the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma because the girl had fallen through the alcohol and had slammed her head, Ritchey said.
"That was very scary," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been deadly for my child.
Lopez has advised parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic products or disinfectant wipes and store hand disinfectants out of the reach of the child.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants were associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand sanitizers containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect that the product contained methanol, a lethal solution, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth grade students in New York State planned to poison their “common” teacher by laying antibacterial products around the classroom, according to a police report.
