The girl later woke up and discovered that the phone was missing and found it in the hand of the sleeping Hogg.
She looked through it, found the confusing messages and immediately alerted her mother.
The police took care of it and saw the five images, then analyzed computers found under the address and discovered "relevant" web searches using terms for finding improper images of children.
Hogg then claimed to the officials that he did so because it would “leade pedophiles on the internet” and he then “pretended to be a police officer to scare them.”
Prosecutor Eilidh Robertson told Dundee Sheriff Court: "He said it was an addiction -- that he was addicted to scaring people.
He admitted that the searches on the computer were done by him, but said it had happened because he wanted to claim to be a police officer to scare pedophiles.
He was asked about his conversations with the unknown person who sent him the pictures and whom he asked to send even more photos.
He said he did it to entice her.
He said he was sick in the head when he drank, and said he wanted to see pictures of rape and murder.
Ms Robertson added: “When the girl found the messages on the phone, she called her mother and was trembling and crying.
She then also saw the indecent pictures on the phone and confronted the defendant with them.
The girl was interviewed and said the defendant was using computers and Playstation to talk to girls who looked much younger than he.
Hogg, 23, Ward Road, Dundee, pleaded guilty to the indictment of taking indecent pictures of children on June 14 last year, violating the requirements on January 25 of this year, and not appearing in court for a hearing on March 24 of this year.
Defense attorney Gregor Sim asked that Hogg not appear in the register of sexual offenders, as it could be argued that "no significant sexual element" could be found in his offence.
