JVA Berlin-Tegel: Five square meters of cell are indignity
The Federal Constitutional Court has righted an ex-detainee of the Tegel Prison, who had been in a too small cell for months.
Because of the violation of their human dignity, prisoners are generally entitled to financial compensation if they are housed in too small cells.
This was decided by the Federal Constitutional Court in a decision published on Wednesday.
According to the judges, those concerned can hope for money even if they were confined for only a few days in the confined spaces (Az.: 1 BvR 1127/14).
A former prisoner was thus successful with his constitutional complaint in Karlsruhe: he was housed in a single cell with about five square meters of floor space in the Berlin-Tegel Prison between June and November 2009; the toilet was not spatially separated.
After that, the man, who according to his lawyer is now free again, had been transferred to a larger cell.
His liability action for unworthy detention conditions against the state of Berlin failed.
But the constitutional judges upheld the judgment of the Berlin Chamber Court and turned the case back there for re-examination.
You see the human dignity of the man violated.
The Court of Appeal now decides on the amount of compensation
Even if, for legal reasons, only a few days of imprisonment were decisive for the compensation, there was a claim for compensation.
Otherwise, "a deterioration in the legal protection of the personality would be to be feared."
The Court of Appeal must now clarify the amount of the compensation.
In the past, constitutional judges have often strengthened the rights of prisoners.
In April, they agreed to indemnify a prisoner for his naked imprisonment in a cell.
According to a 2011 decision, the multiple occupancy of a cell without a separate toilet is also unworthy.
Karlsruhe also confirmed on Wednesday the Berlin Constitutional Court, which had certified a prisoner in a parallel case in November 2009 an inhumane accommodation.
The plaintiff at the time was housed daily for between 15 and 21 hours for three months in a cell of the same type as in the Karlsruhe case.
The Berlin prisons had also been in the headlines in recent weeks due to lack of staff.
Prisoners are therefore repeatedly locked up for 23 hours, the aggressiveness increases, even fighting is said to have already occurred due to the tense situation.
According to the Judicial Press Office, 21 jobs in Tegel are not filled due to a shortage of young people, 19 are expected to be omitted in 2016.
