Refugees with a residence permit or tolerance will no longer receive benefits under the Asylum Requirements Act when they start studying.
In principle, the latter do not receive bafög, since they do not fall under the circle of bafög-eligible persons.
Patient refugees had to have lived in Germany for four years to be eligible for Bafög, from 1 January 2016 this period is shortened to 15 months.
This funding gap must also be closed, however, demands Steffen Krach, Berlin’s secretary of state for science, and the Deutsche Studentenwerk.
Students should get bafög immediately.
Islam will play a more important role in the future, because many refugees are Muslims, and for many, religion is an important part of their identity.
The state should gradually grant Islam the same rights as the churches, and develop the existing state-church right into a new state-religion relationship.
It would also be important to establish an Islamic welfare association that takes care of the new arrivals professionally.
Rights also include duties.
Thus, the representatives of Islam must agree on clear contacts and be ready to cooperate with the state in many areas and give it certain control options.
This includes a willingness to act heartily against religious fundamentalism.
The chairman of the Central Council of Muslims, Aiman Mazyek, on Thursday expressed concern that religious conflicts could also be brought into Germany.
Those who wanted to carry out such conflicts in Germany "immediately lost their right to live here, in Germany," he said in the Bavarian Radio.
