In the future, integration will be a subject of society as a whole much more than it is today.
This will also require a change in the majority society, and the reduction of discrimination and racism will become more pressing.
As a result of European decisions, Germany has had an anti-discrimination body and a general equality law for a short decade.
But it is learning very slowly, as the NSU murder series showed, in which police and authorities systematically ignored the racist motive.
Equal opportunities for all: What migrant organizations and the interest groups of non-white Germans have been demanding for a long time and what international agreements such as the Antiracism Convention oblige Germany to do, must become a reality in the next few years if the country is to remain peaceful and its new citizens should use their opportunities - for the benefit of all.
