Robotic cars: government wants to lead the way for Germany
According to the will of the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the change of the car.
The Federal Cabinet decided on Wednesday a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the edge of the IAA car show about a "new era of mobility".
Automated and connected driving will increase traffic safety and reduce traffic congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
Among other things, the strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being built on the Autobahn 9 in Bavaria.
So that the driver "is not burdened with additional liability risks," the federal government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt to the new developments."
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the permissible maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 km/h.
The federal government also wants to work for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, the driver is becoming more and more a passenger.
The technology is primarily based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on highways will be technically possible by 2020.
However, driverless vehicles on public roads are to be expected “only far beyond 2020.”
The authors of the study estimate the value added in the field of driver assistance systems and the highly automated driving functions at the site in Germany to be around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD transport politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the security of the personal data of drivers must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still see self-driving cars with skepticism - much more than French or Americans.
A survey conducted by the Forsa Institute on Wednesday at the AA on behalf of the testing organization Dekra concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous driving cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect only in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, while in the US, 33 percent expect autonomous cars.
However, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to surrender control throughout the entire journey on all roads.
On the highway, this could be imagined in the flowing traffic at least 15 percent, in the traffic jam 45 percent.
One in four would not leave the car in control under any circumstances.
