EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fisheries
The European Commission intends to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fisheries, thereby imposing a significantly higher dose of the neurotoxin on consumers.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, strongly criticised the plans: "Risks and side effects of misguided industrial and environmental policies are being passed on to pregnant women and toddlers with full force," said Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values of the nerve agent for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, should be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic policy reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that on the basis of the still applicable limit values, about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold.
After doubling the limits, only 14.5 per cent would be unavailable.
In return for this easing, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram, according to Foodwatch.
However, Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller fish, such as carp, are usually so low in loads that they already meet the planned maximum levels today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious diversion maneuver that alone helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and is highly enriched via the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn children".
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment explains on its website with regard to the applicable maximum levels that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through coal burning.
The German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written statement from the Federal Environment Ministry to the Greens MP Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube, was "permanently and extensively exceeded," the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.mercury-action.foodwatch.de
